passages.text: 2Q Beat & Raise w/ 2H "Prudent" Bar; Mgmt Follow- Up Takes

KSS reported 2Q adj. EPS of \(\) 0.56\((vs. Street\) \ \(0.30\) ) driven by: (i) - \(4.2\%\) same- store- sales decline ( \(>\) Street - \(4.7\%\) ), (ii) gross margin expansion of \(+28\) bps Y/Y to \(39.9\%\) ( \(=\) Street \(39.9\%\) ), (iii) SG&A deleverage of \(- 32\) bps Y/Y to \(33.8\%\) of revenues (vs. Street \(34.4\%\) ), and (iv) Other Revenues (credit income) down \(4\%\) Y/Y ( \(>\) Street - \(12\%\) Y/Y), equating to a \(4.5\%\) operating margin as \(0\%\) of revenues. Digging deeper, within 2Q's - \(4.2\%\) same- store- sales decline, management cited a sequential improvement month- over- month throughout the quarter on improved traffic (notably in the digital channel) and proprietary brand sales, with July exiting with Flat comp sales growth.

Looking ahead, management raised the FY25 EPS outlook to \(\) 0.50- \\(0.80\) (vs. prior guide \(\) 0.10- \\(0.60\) and above Street \(\) 0.44)\(based on a net sales decline of - 5\%\) to - 6% (vs. prior guide of down 5 - 7% & Street - 5.9%), same- store- sales down - 4% to - 5% (vs. prior guide down - 5 - 6% and above Street - 5.3%), and operating margins of 2.5% to 2.7% (vs. prior guide of 2.2% to 2.6% and Street 2.5%).

On the topline: The midpoint of mgmt's FY25 outlook implies 2H25 same- store- sales - 5% (vs. Street - 2.6%), equating to an implied 2- yr stack of - 13% or \(\sim 400\) bps sequential 2- yr stacked deceleration vs. 1H - 9%, with management characterizing the 2H25 outlook as a "prudent approach to our financial outlook for the remainder of the year" given the macro environment, noting lower- to middle- income customers remain the most challenged & increasingly "prioritizing value and trading down into lower opening price point products." Further, CFO Timm clarified that both 3Q & 4Q are expected to follow a similar comp cadence, which at the high- end of the full- year outlook would point to a consistent - 4% comp decline in 2H (= 1H's - 4% decline), with ongoing uncertainty across the macroeconomic backdrop as offsets to easing Y/Y comparisons. On upside - maintaining 1H25's 2- yr stack of - 9% throughout 2H25 would translate to same- store sales growth roughly Flat Y/Y in 3Q (matching July's exit rate) and a - 2% decline in 4Q, equating to FY25 comp growth of down 2% (> mgmt's - 4% to - 5% outlook).

On the bottom- line: management expects FY25 gross margins to expand 30bps Y/Y below prior guidance of \(+30 - 50\) bps expansion) and SG&A dollars to decline \(+4.0\) to - 4.5% Y/Y (vs. prior guidance for down - 3.5% to - 5% Y/Y and Street up \(0.5\%\) Y/Y). Specifically driving the negative FY25 gross margin expansion to \(+30\) bps (vs. \(+30 - 50\) bps prior) - CFO Timm noted the implied 2H gross margin outlook calling for \(+20\) bps expansion (vs. 1H25 \(+30\) bps Y/Y) "gives us some flexibility to really make sure that we're driving that value" (i.e. competitive pricing/promotions), which is expected to be offset by favorability on inventory management & increased proprietary brand mix.
Model Implications: We model FY25 EPS of \(\) 0.80\((vs. Street\) \ \(0.44\) ) and FY26 EPS of \(\) 0.57\((vs. Street\) \ \(0.47\) ). Remain Underweight raising our Dec '26 price

While KSS has seen positive sales results associated with store initiatives (Sephora, Gifting, Impulse, and Home Decor), the core Apparel, Footwear, and Legacy Home categories continue to experience revenue declines, pointing to market share erosion within US Apparel & Footwear. In addition, we see long- term risk to the longevity of KSS' store fleet, which represents more than \(50\%\) of total Department Stores in the US, according to our work. Adj. Debt/EBITDAR exited 2023 at \(3.6x\) ( \(>m\) gmt's long- term \(\sim 2.5x\) target), with persistent same- store- sales erosion and operating margin deleverage driving leverage \(>4x\) in 2024- 26E by our model. We rate KSS Underweight.
We raise our Dec '26 price target to \(11\) (vs. \(10 prior) based on \(\sim 3.9x\) our FY27 EBITDA, in- line with Kohl's pre- pandemic 10- yr trough multiple.

- 2Q Same-Store-Sales Ahead of Consensus: KSS reported 2Q net sales decline of \(-5.1\%\) Y/Y (above Street \(-5.6\%\) ) based on same-store-sales down \(-4.2\%\) Y/Y (above Street \(-4.7\%\) ) representing a \(-100\) bps sequential 2-year stacked deceleration and a \(-170\) bps 3-year sequential deceleration. On cadence, CFO Timm noted accelerating momentum as the quarter progressed (July \(>\) June \(>\) May) with pent-up weather/seasonal demand in June (vs. May negatively impacted by colder, wetter weather notably over Memorial Day weekend), in addition to strength in back to school sales (in particular backpacks/Kids Footwear & fleece), proprietary brands, and digital sales supporting July comps improving to Flat Y/Y. Importantly, July's Flat Y/Y comp represents a notable acceleration in July 2-year stacks to \(-4.8\%\) > June \(-10.5\%\) > May \(12.0\%\) by our estimates. By channel, management cited digital sales outperformed relative to store sales with both channels still down compared to last year (w/ digital turning positive in July) and marked the second consecutive outperformance of digital relative to stores in 8 quarters, with digital performance "immediately" benefitting from increased coupon eligibility across National Brands (with the first phase rolled out towards the back end of 1Q).

- Digging deeper on category performance: management cited (i) Sephora sales increased \(+3\%\) in 2Q and Flat on same-store basis (decelerating vs. \(1Q + 1\%\) SSS), (ii) Accessories (excluding Beauty) realized growth following improvements in Jewelry assortment (+12% growth Y/Y), (iii) Women's outperformed relative to the group, driven by increased private label mix (w/ private label comparable sales +500bps sequentially to -3% in 2Q) and the reintroduction of the Petites category (w/ 2Q +40% Y/Y supported by brands such as Lauren Conrad, and Simply Vera Vera Wang), (iv) Men's and Kid's sequential moderation on comps due to declines in seasonal assortments (tee's and shorts) partially offset by a stronger performance in opening price point private label brands (Trek Gear and Jumping Beans).

- FY25 GPM Guide Revised to Lower End of Range: KSS reported 2Q gross margins expansion of \(+28\) bps Y/Y (= Street) driven by (i) category mix benefit, (ii) increased private label brand penetration, and (iii) continued strong inventory management (w/inventory ending the quarter \(-5\%\) Y/Y \(

to - 4.5% full year range due to queue line investments & store payroll/supply chain costs associated with pull-forward inventory receipt timing, while 4Q SG&A dollars are expected to decline at the better-end of the - 4% to - 4.5% full year range.

- Balance Sheet Snapshot: KSS ended 2Q with \(174M in cash and cash equivalents (vs. \)153M in 1Q) with \)75M borrowed on the revolver (w/ \(1.5B total capacity) and \)1.5B of long-term debt (vs. \)1.2B in 1Q). Inventory ended the quarter down -5% y/y (vs. +2% 1Q). On capital allocation, KSS paid a dividend of \)0.125 per share (down 75% y/y) for a total of \(28M.
